Time Series Visualization (variable is time(year))

Difference Between Countries (variable is country names)

Time Series Visualization

# create new dataframe for analysis
df_sugar_1 <- data.frame( t( df_sugar[,2:ncol(df_sugar)] ) )
colnames(df_sugar_1) <- countries

df_food_1 <- data.frame( t( df_food[,2:ncol(df_food)] ) )
colnames(df_food_1) <- countries

df_sugar_1$medi <- apply(df_sugar_1, 1, median)
df_food_1$medi <- apply(df_food_1, 1, median)

df_sugar_1$year <-rownames(df_sugar_1)
df_food_1$year <-rownames(df_food_1)

qplot(x=year, y=medi,
      data=df_sugar_1,
      main="median plot of sugar consumption",
      xlab="year", ylab="sugar consumed per capita per day")

qplot(x=year, y=medi,
      data=df_food_1,
      main="median plot of food consumption",
      xlab="year", ylab="Kcal available per capita per day")

Now here’s another way of plotting data. I personally think this kind of long data frame is easier for plotting boxplot

# yet another way of manipulating data

#new key = 'Year', new value = 'Value', we get these structure by keeping on the "X__1" column in the
# original dataframe (aka exclude 'X__1' from being merged)
sugar_long <- df_sugar %>% gather(Year, Value, -X__1)
food_long <- df_food %>% gather(Year, Value, -X__1)
#sugar_long$Year <- as.numeric(sugar_long$Year)
#food_long$Year <- as.numeric(food_long$Year)
ggplot(data = sugar_long, aes(x = Year, y = Value)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  ggtitle('sugar boxplot')

ggplot(data = food_long, aes(x = Year, y = Value)) + 
  geom_boxplot() +
  ggtitle('food boxplot')

Did you notice one single outlier in the year 1961?

Which country has on average over 3500 kcal per capita per day at that time? lol
